1
00:02:19,155 --> 00:02:21,324
[CROWD CHEERING]
[MARCH PLAYING]

2
00:02:59,352 --> 00:03:03,006
[TOWER BELLS RINGING]
The passenger list, sir.

3
00:03:03,076 --> 00:03:06,256
Oh, very good.

4
00:03:06,310 --> 00:03:09,480
[DISTANT MARCH PLAYING]

5
00:03:11,028 --> 00:03:13,346
[SEAGULLS CAWING]

6
00:03:13,390 --> 00:03:15,510
Who are the Edmunds boys,
private Brooke?

7
00:03:15,552 --> 00:03:17,162
Three brothers, sir,

8
00:03:17,190 --> 00:03:20,293
All posted to south Africa
on the same day...

9
00:03:20,352 --> 00:03:22,314
My birthday in fact, sir.

10
00:03:22,352 --> 00:03:25,105
Is that so, Brooke?

11
00:03:33,351 --> 00:03:36,650
I don't believe it.

12
00:03:36,710 --> 00:03:39,028
Is that...?

13
00:03:39,070 --> 00:03:41,948
What on earth is he doing down here?

14
00:03:45,311 --> 00:03:47,509
Get down to the waterfront, Brooke.

15
00:03:47,548 --> 00:03:49,473
Get customs to pull
this chap to one side...

16
00:03:49,509 --> 00:03:52,611
Van Diemen, south African Boer.

17
00:03:52,667 --> 00:03:54,395
- Escort him here, please.
- Yes, sir.

18
00:03:54,428 --> 00:03:58,121
Tell him...
tell him

19
00:03:58,190 --> 00:04:01,135
Major Carlysle would
very much like to see him.

20
00:04:01,190 --> 00:04:03,234
Yes, sir.

21
00:04:05,346 --> 00:04:06,995
This one's short.
Get me another.

22
00:04:07,027 --> 00:04:08,991
Man:
<i>Yes, sir.</i>

23
00:04:09,028 --> 00:04:11,776
[HORSE NEIGHS]

24
00:04:11,825 --> 00:04:13,553
Brooke,

25
00:04:13,585 --> 00:04:15,745
Where are you off to in such a hurry?

26
00:04:15,786 --> 00:04:17,632
I've been asked to escort
one of them Boers.

27
00:04:17,669 --> 00:04:19,356
The major wants to see him.

28
00:04:19,385 --> 00:04:22,096
Let me have a look at that.

29
00:04:25,068 --> 00:04:27,228
We should have hung
them all, shouldn't we,

30
00:04:27,268 --> 00:04:28,838
Instead of giving them
a king's pardon?

31
00:04:28,867 --> 00:04:30,953
What's his name?

32
00:04:33,068 --> 00:04:35,464
Bloody hell.

33
00:04:35,504 --> 00:04:38,423
With me, Brooke.

34
00:04:42,264 --> 00:04:45,267
[CHILDREN CHATTERING, LAUGHING]

35
00:04:51,663 --> 00:04:54,082
Woman:
Come on, girls.

36
00:04:57,425 --> 00:04:59,585
Next, please.

37
00:04:59,626 --> 00:05:01,336
<i>Oi.</i>

38
00:05:10,023 --> 00:05:14,539
Uh, Mr. Van Dimon.

39
00:05:14,621 --> 00:05:18,157
Diemen...
Van Diemen.

40
00:05:18,223 --> 00:05:20,382
So, Mr. Van Dimon,
what brings you

41
00:05:20,422 --> 00:05:23,054
All the way to our remote
little corner of the world?

42
00:05:23,102 --> 00:05:26,087
Well, I'm curious.

43
00:05:26,142 --> 00:05:28,106
Curious?

44
00:05:28,143 --> 00:05:30,852
You'd have to be very curious
to travel thousands of Miles.

45
00:05:30,901 --> 00:05:33,414
Bloody right, I'm curious.

46
00:05:33,463 --> 00:05:35,427
I'm very curious to find out

47
00:05:35,461 --> 00:05:37,424
Why you boys crossed two oceans

48
00:05:37,460 --> 00:05:40,210
To help the British burn down my farm.

49
00:05:40,261 --> 00:05:42,096
Well...

50
00:05:46,980 --> 00:05:49,941
Arjan Van Diemen.

51
00:05:50,542 --> 00:05:54,038
[CROWD MURMURING]

52
00:05:54,100 --> 00:05:56,063
And I thought the war was finished.

53
00:05:56,100 --> 00:05:58,063
Not for you, you murdering bastard.

54
00:05:58,100 --> 00:06:00,378
You're under arrest.

55
00:06:00,419 --> 00:06:03,130
Give it over.

56
00:06:06,299 --> 00:06:07,925
Go on.

57
00:06:32,416 --> 00:06:34,773
Go on.

58
00:06:34,815 --> 00:06:38,585
Give him his rifle back.

59
00:06:38,656 --> 00:06:39,865
Now, you bloody fool!

60
00:06:43,455 --> 00:06:45,890
Put your weapon away.

61
00:06:45,935 --> 00:06:47,741
Do you know who this is?

62
00:06:47,777 --> 00:06:50,029
That'll be all.
Thank you, Saunders.

63
00:06:51,097 --> 00:06:52,707
Jesus.

64
00:06:52,734 --> 00:06:56,613
Don't make me write you up.

65
00:06:59,815 --> 00:07:01,739
Get back to the docks, Brooke.

66
00:07:01,774 --> 00:07:04,170
Give some real soldiers
a hero's welcome.

67
00:07:04,213 --> 00:07:06,177
Yes, sir.

68
00:07:06,215 --> 00:07:09,317
[DISTANT BOAT HORN BLARING]

69
00:07:09,374 --> 00:07:12,335
Apologies for the undignified welcome, Mr.
Van Diemen.

70
00:07:14,813 --> 00:07:18,191
Saunders there was
with me in south Africa.

71
00:07:18,254 --> 00:07:20,729
He seems to have forgotten
the war's over.

72
00:07:20,776 --> 00:07:22,503
I'm sure you understand.

73
00:07:22,535 --> 00:07:24,537
Mm.

74
00:07:39,814 --> 00:07:42,358
So you do exist.

75
00:07:43,969 --> 00:07:46,679
I led a detachment of cavalry

76
00:07:46,729 --> 00:07:50,383
For nearly two years
trying to catch up with you.

77
00:07:50,451 --> 00:07:52,846
We chased you clean
across the Transvaal

78
00:07:52,891 --> 00:07:54,855
Whilst you caused havoc.

79
00:07:54,893 --> 00:07:58,271
And you, major...

80
00:07:58,331 --> 00:08:01,125
You couldn't even catch
a simple farmer.

81
00:08:03,491 --> 00:08:05,336
What's your plan here, Van Diemen?

82
00:08:05,371 --> 00:08:06,863
You're a long way from home.

83
00:08:06,891 --> 00:08:08,343
You too.

84
00:08:08,371 --> 00:08:10,963
On the contrary,
this is home for me now.

85
00:08:11,009 --> 00:08:12,934
Home?

86
00:08:12,970 --> 00:08:15,012
Huh.

87
00:08:15,048 --> 00:08:19,177
Home these days seems to be most
of the globe to you British.

88
00:08:25,289 --> 00:08:28,706
So are you planning
on buying some land here,

89
00:08:28,768 --> 00:08:32,647
Perhaps take up farming again?

90
00:08:37,887 --> 00:08:41,724
No, I guess we didn't
leave you with much, did we?

91
00:08:50,245 --> 00:08:52,248
Well, for what it's worth,
Mr. Van Diemen,

92
00:08:52,286 --> 00:08:55,498
I hope you do find your new home here.

93
00:09:10,725 --> 00:09:13,311
[MUSIC PLAYING]
[PEOPLE LAUGHING]

94
00:09:21,005 --> 00:09:23,174
[HORSE SNORTING]

95
00:09:27,324 --> 00:09:29,367
Come here.

96
00:09:33,883 --> 00:09:36,511
What is this?

97
00:09:39,684 --> 00:09:41,726
It's a piece of home.

98
00:09:41,762 --> 00:09:43,646
- Home?
- Mm-hmm.

99
00:09:43,682 --> 00:09:46,197
What do you mean, home?

100
00:09:46,244 --> 00:09:48,663
It belonged to my grandfather.

101
00:09:51,283 --> 00:09:53,796
Sometimes he would cry over this.

102
00:09:53,844 --> 00:09:56,121
Looks like sand to me...

103
00:09:56,161 --> 00:09:58,831
Red sand.

104
00:10:02,602 --> 00:10:05,235
[SPEAKS MAORI]

105
00:10:05,281 --> 00:10:08,540
You're very pretty.

106
00:10:08,600 --> 00:10:11,311
There's a lot prettier in this town.

107
00:10:11,361 --> 00:10:14,031
Some of them officers' wives, they...

108
00:10:14,079 --> 00:10:16,041
No no no no, I've seen
lots of women...

109
00:10:16,078 --> 00:10:19,024
Wahine on Tahiti.

110
00:10:19,078 --> 00:10:22,415
You could be a Princess there.

111
00:10:41,799 --> 00:10:43,723
Take your hands off me.
I'm quite capable

112
00:10:43,757 --> 00:10:45,801
Of walking by myself.

113
00:10:47,959 --> 00:10:51,650
Come on, sergeant.
You've had a bit too much.

114
00:10:51,718 --> 00:10:53,682
Goes with the rank, corporal Drake,

115
00:10:53,717 --> 00:10:55,680
- With the rank.
- Yes, your highness.

116
00:10:55,718 --> 00:10:57,682
"goes with the rank."

117
00:10:57,719 --> 00:10:59,682
Oh, watch yourself there, Teddy.

118
00:10:59,717 --> 00:11:01,680
Don't you "Teddy" me.

119
00:11:01,717 --> 00:11:04,136
Oh, hey. Oi.

120
00:11:07,277 --> 00:11:09,240
There's a lantern on

121
00:11:09,274 --> 00:11:12,142
In the stables.

122
00:11:12,195 --> 00:11:13,922
[DOOR RATTLING]

123
00:11:13,956 --> 00:11:16,375
I'll have his guts for garters.

124
00:11:22,276 --> 00:11:25,065
<i>Well well well,</i>

125
00:11:25,116 --> 00:11:28,995
<i>What have we here?</i>

126
00:11:30,834 --> 00:11:34,410
If it isn't young Lucy

127
00:11:34,473 --> 00:11:37,064
And a bloody savage.

128
00:11:37,115 --> 00:11:39,039
<i>What are you two doing in here,</i>

129
00:11:39,074 --> 00:11:41,941
Besides the obvious?

130
00:11:41,993 --> 00:11:44,388
I don't think I know you.

131
00:11:44,435 --> 00:11:46,398
Do you know him?

132
00:11:46,432 --> 00:11:49,025
Never seen him.

133
00:11:49,073 --> 00:11:51,951
<i>Wonder where he gets his money from.</i>

134
00:11:54,153 --> 00:11:58,080
Weren't interested
in our horses, were you?

135
00:11:58,152 --> 00:12:00,469
He's talking to you.

136
00:12:00,514 --> 00:12:02,870
You think he understands English?

137
00:12:02,914 --> 00:12:05,467
[CHUCKLES]

138
00:12:05,513 --> 00:12:07,477
Anyway,

139
00:12:07,512 --> 00:12:11,057
You're trespassing on army property.

140
00:12:13,831 --> 00:12:16,502
I think a thrashing might be in order,

141
00:12:16,552 --> 00:12:18,790
Gentlemen, eh?

142
00:12:18,830 --> 00:12:22,207
Now come and take your punishment

143
00:12:22,272 --> 00:12:25,400
Like a good little savage.

144
00:12:28,872 --> 00:12:32,289
- Hold him up.
- Get up.

145
00:12:32,353 --> 00:12:35,692
Eh?

146
00:12:35,750 --> 00:12:38,544
I'll teach you to mess with our women.

147
00:12:47,508 --> 00:12:49,040
[GRUNTS]

148
00:12:49,069 --> 00:12:51,112
Get up.

149
00:12:52,910 --> 00:12:54,953
[HORSES WHINNY]

150
00:13:03,068 --> 00:13:05,196
[SPEAKS MAORI]

151
00:13:07,229 --> 00:13:09,940
- What did you say?
- Leave him alone, you bastards.

152
00:13:21,428 --> 00:13:23,638
You should have taken
your thrashing, boy.

153
00:13:34,505 --> 00:13:36,507
Savage!

154
00:13:38,346 --> 00:13:39,681
Christ, you bloody...

155
00:13:43,704 --> 00:13:45,628
[SAUNDERS SHOUTS]

156
00:13:45,665 --> 00:13:47,625
[LUCY SCREAMS]

157
00:13:50,384 --> 00:13:52,762
Jesus Christ.

158
00:13:56,422 --> 00:14:00,009
Jesus.
Jesus Christ.

159
00:14:01,385 --> 00:14:05,272
You bloody killed him.
You bloody killed him.

160
00:14:05,344 --> 00:14:07,346
You bloody killed him.

161
00:14:10,624 --> 00:14:13,627
We need a doctor.

162
00:14:15,022 --> 00:14:16,899
Get a bloody doctor!

163
00:14:17,864 --> 00:14:19,827
[PANTING, MOANS]

164
00:14:19,862 --> 00:14:22,031
[MEN CHATTERING]

165
00:14:31,342 --> 00:14:33,385
[SIGHS]

166
00:14:35,502 --> 00:14:38,880
[SAUNDERS MOANS]

167
00:14:38,940 --> 00:14:41,532
Sir...
[LUCY CRYING]

168
00:14:41,581 --> 00:14:43,387
You walked into the stables

169
00:14:43,420 --> 00:14:45,187
And he simply attacked you?

170
00:14:45,221 --> 00:14:46,399
Yes, sir.

171
00:14:46,422 --> 00:14:48,699
Unprovoked?

172
00:14:48,739 --> 00:14:51,158
Well, we did ask him
what he was doing in there.

173
00:14:52,339 --> 00:14:54,302
<i>We thought he was after the horses.</i>

174
00:14:54,339 --> 00:14:57,167
- That was all?
- Yes, sir.

175
00:14:57,220 --> 00:14:59,180
Levin.

176
00:15:00,061 --> 00:15:03,106
That was about the way of it.

177
00:15:10,178 --> 00:15:12,769
And this was the way of it?

178
00:15:12,817 --> 00:15:15,487
[CRYING]

179
00:15:17,219 --> 00:15:19,929
Yes, sir.

180
00:15:19,980 --> 00:15:21,944
That were the way of it.

181
00:15:21,980 --> 00:15:25,435
Yes, sir.

182
00:15:25,497 --> 00:15:28,050
He was off that whaler
that came in yesterday.

183
00:15:28,096 --> 00:15:30,727
Sergeant Leybourne.

184
00:15:30,777 --> 00:15:33,134
I don't think our man
will be getting far, sir.

185
00:15:33,177 --> 00:15:35,297
Let's make sure he doesn't.

186
00:15:35,336 --> 00:15:37,811
He's been seen heading
off up the coast.

187
00:15:37,857 --> 00:15:39,899
I'll need half a dozen men.

188
00:15:39,938 --> 00:15:41,861
That should be enough.
And horses.

189
00:15:41,896 --> 00:15:43,938
He's on foot, so we'll
soon catch up with him.

190
00:15:43,976 --> 00:15:45,429
What about dogs?

191
00:15:45,455 --> 00:15:47,497
No, no dogs.
This isn't a blood sport.

192
00:15:47,537 --> 00:15:49,894
I won't have it turned into one.

193
00:15:49,938 --> 00:15:52,490
Now that local scout...

194
00:15:52,537 --> 00:15:53,989
Mr. Bryce, sir.

195
00:15:54,017 --> 00:15:55,823
Yes, Bryce.
I want him here,

196
00:15:55,854 --> 00:15:57,661
Fully provisioned within the hour.

197
00:15:57,696 --> 00:16:00,741
We'll leave at first light. See to it.

198
00:16:13,254 --> 00:16:15,807
Van Diemen.

199
00:16:15,855 --> 00:16:18,190
I don't suppose you saw anything?

200
00:16:22,695 --> 00:16:25,322
You know, we could use
another good tracker.

201
00:16:26,574 --> 00:16:29,363
The reward is 100 sovereigns...

202
00:16:29,412 --> 00:16:32,711
100 sovereigns alive, 25 if dead.

203
00:16:32,774 --> 00:16:35,277
That's a lot of money.

204
00:16:42,291 --> 00:16:44,569
You see that man?

205
00:16:44,610 --> 00:16:47,831
He butchered British officers.

206
00:16:47,891 --> 00:16:50,366
I don't want that scum
anywhere near me.

207
00:16:50,414 --> 00:16:52,337
That needn't trouble you,
sergeant major.

208
00:16:52,371 --> 00:16:54,060
You shan't be accompanying us.

209
00:16:54,092 --> 00:16:57,116
You and Corporal Levin are in no
fit state to be chasing anybody.

210
00:16:57,171 --> 00:16:59,674
The pair of you
will return to barracks.

211
00:17:02,053 --> 00:17:04,016
I trust I make myself clear.

212
00:17:04,048 --> 00:17:06,798
Yes, sir.

213
00:17:06,852 --> 00:17:08,854
- Well?
- Yes, sir.

214
00:17:08,891 --> 00:17:13,329
Look, when I arrived
yesterday at the harbor,

215
00:17:13,409 --> 00:17:15,372
I didn't see any whaler.

216
00:17:15,408 --> 00:17:17,804
They left without him
on the afternoon tide.

217
00:17:17,848 --> 00:17:19,811
The skipper was angry as hell,

218
00:17:19,849 --> 00:17:22,402
Charging around, shouting at
everybody if they'd seen him.

219
00:17:22,450 --> 00:17:24,532
I tell you, I was near
to locking him up.

220
00:17:24,571 --> 00:17:26,574
Why so angry?

221
00:17:26,611 --> 00:17:28,574
Well, he'd lost his
harpoonist, didn't he?

222
00:17:28,609 --> 00:17:31,201
A good harpoon man's
worth gold these days.

223
00:17:31,248 --> 00:17:33,211
These all his belongings?

224
00:17:33,247 --> 00:17:36,782
Yeah, these and his
kit bag over there.

225
00:17:36,850 --> 00:17:39,353
- That too?
- Yeah.

226
00:17:45,527 --> 00:17:47,647
[SEAGULLS CAWING]

227
00:17:47,687 --> 00:17:49,898
[HORSES WHINNY]

228
00:18:12,925 --> 00:18:14,969
[GROANING]

229
00:18:52,364 --> 00:18:55,117
[HORSES WHINNYING]

230
00:19:02,883 --> 00:19:05,427
[PANTING, COUGHS]

231
00:19:21,799 --> 00:19:23,252
Carlysle:
All right, dismount.

232
00:19:23,282 --> 00:19:25,245
Sergeant Leybourne,
these horses need a rest,

233
00:19:25,282 --> 00:19:27,243
- Just a few minutes.
- Yes, sir.

234
00:19:29,399 --> 00:19:31,874
Mr. Bryce, what is it?

235
00:19:31,923 --> 00:19:34,358
Maori.

236
00:19:34,400 --> 00:19:37,935
<i>See? </i> The weight's
<i>all on the toes.</i>

237
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:40,669
No heel print.

238
00:19:43,278 --> 00:19:45,241
The weight's right.

239
00:19:45,277 --> 00:19:49,245
By the spacing...
his height.

240
00:19:49,319 --> 00:19:51,530
It's him.

241
00:19:52,757 --> 00:19:55,900
If he keeps heading up this coast,

242
00:19:55,958 --> 00:19:58,118
He'll reach Dunney's Point,

243
00:19:58,158 --> 00:20:00,632
<i>Find a boat... whew,</i>

244
00:20:00,681 --> 00:20:02,565
Away at sea 'fore you know it.

245
00:20:02,598 --> 00:20:03,933
Very well.

246
00:20:03,955 --> 00:20:05,801
Private barker!</i>
Sir.</i>

247
00:20:05,837 --> 00:20:08,940
<i>Get up on those rocks, man, see if
we can't get around the headland</i>

248
00:20:08,998 --> 00:20:11,041
Before the tide</i> comes in. Yes, sir.</i>

249
00:20:36,994 --> 00:20:39,271
Mr. Van Diemen,
is there a problem?

250
00:20:39,313 --> 00:20:41,816
It's not him.

251
00:20:43,436 --> 00:20:45,989
No disrespect
to Mr. Bryce here,

252
00:20:46,036 --> 00:20:48,903
<i>But our man was used to wearing shoes.</i>

253
00:20:48,954 --> 00:20:50,995
This man,

254
00:20:51,035 --> 00:20:54,571
Whoever he was...
he never wore shoes.

255
00:20:54,636 --> 00:20:56,285
[SPITS]

256
00:20:56,316 --> 00:20:59,379
With respect, major,

257
00:20:59,436 --> 00:21:03,565
I don't think our man
is just another sailor.

258
00:21:05,154 --> 00:21:07,657
I think he's coming home.

259
00:21:11,270 --> 00:21:13,981
[MAN PANTING]

260
00:21:55,671 --> 00:21:58,224
Sir, if we go right away,

261
00:21:58,271 --> 00:22:00,901
We should be able to get around
before the tide cuts us off.

262
00:22:00,950 --> 00:22:03,328
Thank you, barker.

263
00:22:05,029 --> 00:22:07,031
All right, mount up!

264
00:22:09,148 --> 00:22:11,308
Van Diemen!

265
00:22:11,348 --> 00:22:13,587
<i>Van Diemen!</i>

266
00:22:13,630 --> 00:22:16,340
Blast the man.
Barker, get his horse.

267
00:22:16,388 --> 00:22:18,348
Yes, sir.

268
00:22:48,544 --> 00:22:50,463
[GROANS]

269
00:24:08,259 --> 00:24:09,554
Mr. Bryce.

270
00:24:09,579 --> 00:24:12,123
Mr. Bryce.

271
00:24:13,659 --> 00:24:15,505
Your man left
empty-handed, didn't he?

272
00:24:15,537 --> 00:24:17,414
That's right.

273
00:24:18,738 --> 00:24:21,408
Your Mr. Van Diemen
was right.

274
00:24:24,741 --> 00:24:27,176
Raupo bread.

275
00:24:27,218 --> 00:24:29,064
<i>Maori pollen bread.</i>

276
00:24:29,100 --> 00:24:31,534
<i>Where would he get that?</i>

277
00:24:31,578 --> 00:24:33,896
Look at the size of this fire.

278
00:24:33,940 --> 00:24:35,745
[CHUCKLES]

279
00:24:35,776 --> 00:24:38,211
Whoever this fellow was,
he was in no hurry.

280
00:24:38,257 --> 00:24:41,006
Mr. Bryce, are you
seriously telling me

281
00:24:41,058 --> 00:24:43,218
That we've been following
the wrong man all day?

282
00:24:43,257 --> 00:24:46,753
Same build, same height,

283
00:24:46,818 --> 00:24:49,371
Wrong Maori.
[LAUGHS]

284
00:24:49,420 --> 00:24:52,011
I knew we should have
gotten bloody dogs.

285
00:24:52,057 --> 00:24:53,941
We'll double back, pick up the trail

286
00:24:53,975 --> 00:24:56,922
Where our Mr. Van Diemen
disappeared on us.

287
00:24:56,976 --> 00:24:58,781
And you're quite certain
you can do that?

288
00:24:58,816 --> 00:25:01,094
I'll have two trails to
follow instead of just one.

289
00:25:01,137 --> 00:25:03,681
Well, we'd better get on
with it then, haven't we?

290
00:25:44,692 --> 00:25:46,819
[FLIES BUZZING]

291
00:26:06,413 --> 00:26:09,166
Mm, been fishing, eh?

292
00:26:13,332 --> 00:26:15,375
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

293
00:26:41,047 --> 00:26:43,049
[WINCES]

294
00:27:28,285 --> 00:27:29,995
[WATCH TICKING]

295
00:27:43,845 --> 00:27:45,972
[RUSTLING]

296
00:28:20,520 --> 00:28:23,315
Head, feet.

297
00:28:27,360 --> 00:28:29,520
So you knew I was watching you, eh?

298
00:28:29,560 --> 00:28:31,646
Good.

299
00:28:33,798 --> 00:28:35,842
Mm.

300
00:28:42,240 --> 00:28:44,284
[SNIFFS]

301
00:28:56,001 --> 00:28:58,396
So you've made yourself some shoes?

302
00:28:58,440 --> 00:29:01,234
Mm, clever boy.

303
00:29:59,357 --> 00:30:02,145
<i>Horses won't be much use to
us from here on, major.</i>

304
00:30:02,193 --> 00:30:05,492
Al right.
Thank you, Mr. Bryce.

305
00:30:05,553 --> 00:30:08,105
- Private barker.
- Yes, sir?

306
00:30:08,152 --> 00:30:10,744
You'll take these horses
back to base in the morning.

307
00:30:10,791 --> 00:30:11,969
Yes, sir.

308
00:30:11,991 --> 00:30:13,719
- Crowther.
- Yes, major?

309
00:30:13,752 --> 00:30:15,670
- We'll keep yours as a packhorse.
- Sir.

310
00:30:21,473 --> 00:30:24,059
[BIRDS CALLING]

311
00:32:14,346 --> 00:32:16,515
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

312
00:32:20,623 --> 00:32:23,042
[INSECT BUZZING]

313
00:32:27,303 --> 00:32:29,471
[EXHALES]

314
00:32:43,100 --> 00:32:45,603
[RUSTLING]
[WINGS FLUTTERING]

315
00:33:28,261 --> 00:33:30,263
Do not move

316
00:33:30,298 --> 00:33:32,592
Unless I tell you to.

317
00:33:35,377 --> 00:33:37,796
[SPEAKING MAORI]

318
00:33:40,016 --> 00:33:42,269
I said do not move.

319
00:33:44,539 --> 00:33:46,583
Stand still.

320
00:33:49,818 --> 00:33:51,899
Stop.

321
00:33:51,938 --> 00:33:53,273
Shut up.

322
00:33:53,297 --> 00:33:54,592
[GUNSHOT]

323
00:33:54,619 --> 00:33:56,871
Argh! Bloody hell.

324
00:34:00,820 --> 00:34:04,629
That's better, eh?

325
00:34:04,695 --> 00:34:07,281
How much are they paying you for me?

326
00:34:08,894 --> 00:34:10,149
How much?

327
00:34:10,174 --> 00:34:12,571
100 sovereigns alive, 25 dead.

328
00:34:12,617 --> 00:34:14,344
25?

329
00:34:14,374 --> 00:34:16,024
Mm.

330
00:34:16,055 --> 00:34:19,471
A lot of people
would be happy with 25.

331
00:34:19,535 --> 00:34:22,481
Lucky I got you.

332
00:34:22,536 --> 00:34:25,164
If I have to kill you, I will.

333
00:34:28,495 --> 00:34:31,126
Mind you, anybody
who'd be happy with 25

334
00:34:31,176 --> 00:34:33,375
Would probably be
too stupid to find me.

335
00:34:33,415 --> 00:34:35,340
Yeah, they would.

336
00:34:35,376 --> 00:34:38,164
That's 75 sovereigns'
difference alive or dead.

337
00:34:38,214 --> 00:34:40,177
I'll tell you what:

338
00:34:40,213 --> 00:34:42,177
What will you give me if I promise

339
00:34:42,213 --> 00:34:45,007
- Not to choke myself to death?
- Just walk.

340
00:34:54,892 --> 00:34:57,061
What are you reading?

341
00:34:59,973 --> 00:35:02,851
Hey, I asked you a question.

342
00:35:07,211 --> 00:35:09,999
That "the wicked will perish.

343
00:35:10,051 --> 00:35:12,014
The enemies of the Lord

344
00:35:12,051 --> 00:35:14,290
Shall be as the fat
of lambs."

345
00:35:14,332 --> 00:35:16,373
Mm.

346
00:35:16,409 --> 00:35:19,663
"but the righteous
showeth mercy, and giveth."

347
00:35:21,812 --> 00:35:23,606
The 37th psalm.

348
00:35:24,771 --> 00:35:27,677
I spent a lot of time
in a missionary school.

349
00:35:27,732 --> 00:35:30,560
That's where I learned to read.

350
00:35:30,613 --> 00:35:33,480
You're an educated man.

351
00:35:33,530 --> 00:35:36,991
Does that make a difference?

352
00:35:40,210 --> 00:35:42,135
Perhaps.

353
00:35:42,168 --> 00:35:44,253
Why?

354
00:35:48,128 --> 00:35:52,330
Because education distinguishes

355
00:35:52,409 --> 00:35:54,884
The civilized man from the savage.

356
00:35:54,929 --> 00:35:57,953
Ah, there are no savages here then.

357
00:35:58,009 --> 00:36:00,287
The missionaries taught
us all to read...

358
00:36:00,329 --> 00:36:03,274
All of us.

359
00:36:03,327 --> 00:36:06,509
My father could quote your
bible from cover to cover.

360
00:36:06,571 --> 00:36:09,673
"you cannot know your enemy," he said,

361
00:36:09,725 --> 00:36:13,270
"until you know
his God."

362
00:36:15,087 --> 00:36:17,521
And did he find their God?

363
00:36:17,566 --> 00:36:20,198
Oh yes, he met him

364
00:36:20,248 --> 00:36:22,500
At the end of a rope.

365
00:36:26,765 --> 00:36:29,004
So what's my life worth now?

366
00:36:29,047 --> 00:36:32,975
125 sovereigns?

367
00:36:33,046 --> 00:36:35,590
I am not a killer.

368
00:36:37,806 --> 00:36:40,642
You'll have an honest trial.

369
00:36:43,566 --> 00:36:46,110
I'll get an honest hanging.

370
00:36:52,645 --> 00:36:54,843
What is that?

371
00:36:54,883 --> 00:36:57,083
Let me see.

372
00:36:57,125 --> 00:36:59,210
[SPEAKS MAORI]

373
00:37:00,526 --> 00:37:03,112
You can trust me.

374
00:37:21,524 --> 00:37:25,098
Wife? Daughters?
Pretty.

375
00:37:25,165 --> 00:37:27,638
Van Diemen:
Yeah.

376
00:37:27,681 --> 00:37:29,606
<i>How old are they... your daughters?</i>

377
00:37:29,641 --> 00:37:32,075
Eight, and the twins are six.

378
00:37:32,119 --> 00:37:34,082
<i>And where do they live?</i>

379
00:37:34,120 --> 00:37:36,595
<i>Back in town?</i>

380
00:37:36,641 --> 00:37:40,372
They don't live.

381
00:37:40,441 --> 00:37:43,444
They're buried
in south Africa somewhere.

382
00:37:48,960 --> 00:37:51,004
[SPEAKS MAORI]

383
00:37:54,362 --> 00:37:58,324
[SPEAKS MAORI]

384
00:38:03,078 --> 00:38:06,023
They say when children die, they...

385
00:38:06,077 --> 00:38:08,663
They stay children forever.

386
00:38:26,280 --> 00:38:29,423
You can't start a story
and not finish.

387
00:38:29,480 --> 00:38:31,914
It's not good.

388
00:38:31,955 --> 00:38:34,207
[SPEAKING MAORI]

389
00:38:40,317 --> 00:38:43,028
<i>It's not good for your soul.</i>

390
00:38:48,635 --> 00:38:50,804
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

391
00:38:55,036 --> 00:38:57,580
Stop here.

392
00:38:59,996 --> 00:39:02,040
Two hours.

393
00:39:03,875 --> 00:39:06,210
All right, let's keep moving.

394
00:39:15,155 --> 00:39:17,079
Kereama:
It's just mouku.

395
00:39:17,116 --> 00:39:19,118
You can eat it.

396
00:39:19,153 --> 00:39:21,117
You didn't know that, did you?

397
00:39:21,155 --> 00:39:24,296
Mind you, you weren't brought up here.

398
00:39:24,354 --> 00:39:26,318
You see this?

399
00:39:26,352 --> 00:39:28,355
Meke-meke.

400
00:39:28,393 --> 00:39:30,435
Just a little nibble on that
and you'll be

401
00:39:30,473 --> 00:39:32,986
Spewing your guts out for days.

402
00:39:33,033 --> 00:39:35,619
I shouldn't have
told you that, should I?

403
00:39:44,632 --> 00:39:48,677
"and his blessing covered
the dry land as a River

404
00:39:48,751 --> 00:39:51,500
And watered it
as a flood."

405
00:39:51,550 --> 00:39:54,386
I could build us a raft.

406
00:39:56,993 --> 00:39:59,742
"as he hath turned
the waters into saltiness,

407
00:39:59,792 --> 00:40:03,671
So shall the heathen
inherit his wrath."

408
00:40:14,308 --> 00:40:16,644
[BIRDS CALLING]

409
00:40:28,189 --> 00:40:30,191
Stop.

410
00:40:32,029 --> 00:40:34,657
Sit. Sit.

411
00:40:37,186 --> 00:40:38,646
[GROANS]

412
00:40:59,546 --> 00:41:01,840
[SNORES]

413
00:41:23,943 --> 00:41:25,987
[GUN CLICKS]

414
00:41:31,185 --> 00:41:33,228
<i>Don't move.</i>

415
00:41:34,303 --> 00:41:36,422
I'm not moving.

416
00:41:36,464 --> 00:41:38,841
Turn around slowly.

417
00:41:45,146 --> 00:41:47,776
Drop the pistol.

418
00:41:47,824 --> 00:41:50,142
Drop the pistol!

419
00:41:50,182 --> 00:41:52,027
No.

420
00:41:52,064 --> 00:41:54,342
What?
Drop it.

421
00:41:54,382 --> 00:41:57,091
No.

422
00:41:57,143 --> 00:41:59,932
I'll shoot you.

423
00:41:59,984 --> 00:42:02,537
You know, when I travel

424
00:42:02,582 --> 00:42:04,898
I always keep an empty chamber

425
00:42:04,942 --> 00:42:07,220
In case of accidents.

426
00:42:07,260 --> 00:42:09,381
Before you cock it,

427
00:42:09,421 --> 00:42:12,877
I'll have a bullet between your eyes.

428
00:42:12,939 --> 00:42:14,588
You're lying.

429
00:42:14,622 --> 00:42:16,821
Truth is I'm not really sure.

430
00:42:16,860 --> 00:42:19,688
I've been careless
these past two days.

431
00:42:19,741 --> 00:42:21,705
Of course,

432
00:42:21,743 --> 00:42:24,296
We won't know until
you pull that trigger.

433
00:42:24,341 --> 00:42:26,657
I don't believe you.

434
00:42:26,700 --> 00:42:27,838
Fine.

435
00:42:27,858 --> 00:42:30,057
And I will pull the trigger.

436
00:42:30,102 --> 00:42:31,830
Fine.

437
00:42:31,857 --> 00:42:34,528
Well, if you're right, I'm dead.
If I'm right, you're dead.

438
00:42:34,580 --> 00:42:37,762
But until you pull that
trigger, we won't know.

439
00:42:37,819 --> 00:42:39,703
Drop the gun.

440
00:42:39,739 --> 00:42:41,506
No.

441
00:42:41,538 --> 00:42:43,973
- Drop the gun.
- You drop your gun.

442
00:42:44,017 --> 00:42:47,080
- I'm not dropping my gun.
- I'm not dropping my gun.

443
00:42:47,137 --> 00:42:49,100
Fine.

444
00:42:49,138 --> 00:42:51,063
Let's just walk to shore.

445
00:42:51,100 --> 00:42:53,692
And keep your hands
where I can see them.

446
00:42:53,740 --> 00:42:55,271
No. No.

447
00:42:55,299 --> 00:42:57,223
I will pull the trigger.

448
00:42:57,258 --> 00:43:00,203
<i>I'll take my chances.</i>

449
00:43:00,258 --> 00:43:02,890
My legs are getting cold.

450
00:43:02,939 --> 00:43:05,570
You should have stayed
over there where it's dry.

451
00:43:05,616 --> 00:43:09,151
You are the most annoying man
I have ever met.

452
00:43:09,216 --> 00:43:11,376
I should kill you
for just being annoying.

453
00:43:11,417 --> 00:43:13,301
I thought you weren't a killer.

454
00:43:13,337 --> 00:43:15,379
I'm not, or I would have
shot you right away.

455
00:43:15,416 --> 00:43:17,694
In which case you'd be dead.

456
00:43:17,738 --> 00:43:20,407
Well, we don't know that yet, do we?

457
00:43:23,976 --> 00:43:25,939
I'd like a smoke.

458
00:43:25,974 --> 00:43:27,702
No.

459
00:43:27,737 --> 00:43:29,322
[TWEETS]

460
00:43:30,456 --> 00:43:31,957
[GUNSHOT]

461
00:43:43,933 --> 00:43:46,018
[WHISPERS] Damn you.

462
00:43:50,496 --> 00:43:52,539
Damn you.

463
00:44:03,173 --> 00:44:05,019
Come on, come on.

464
00:44:05,055 --> 00:44:07,974
[GRUNTING]

465
00:44:13,011 --> 00:44:16,075
They meet here separately.

466
00:44:16,133 --> 00:44:18,097
Hold there.

467
00:44:18,134 --> 00:44:20,686
There's two now.

468
00:44:20,734 --> 00:44:23,011
- Both of them? Two men, both of them?
- There's two.

469
00:44:23,053 --> 00:44:25,097
- All right, which way?
- This way.

470
00:44:31,369 --> 00:44:33,175
Sa-bine.

471
00:44:33,211 --> 00:44:35,921
Sabine.

472
00:44:35,972 --> 00:44:38,600
Is that your wife?

473
00:44:39,651 --> 00:44:41,654
What language is this?

474
00:44:41,689 --> 00:44:43,613
I told you

475
00:44:43,649 --> 00:44:46,987
I'm from south Africa.

476
00:44:47,048 --> 00:44:49,801
You're one of them Boers.

477
00:44:52,330 --> 00:44:55,471
Sounds like a bushpig.

478
00:44:55,529 --> 00:44:57,964
[SPEAKS MAORI]

479
00:44:58,010 --> 00:45:00,249
"Boer"...

480
00:45:00,291 --> 00:45:01,939
It means "farmer."

481
00:45:01,965 --> 00:45:05,427
You're the strangest
farmer I've ever met.

482
00:45:11,046 --> 00:45:13,757
You fought the British, didn't you?

483
00:45:16,729 --> 00:45:20,441
My grandfather led our people
against the British.

484
00:45:22,047 --> 00:45:25,504
He was a great leader, a warrior.

485
00:45:25,569 --> 00:45:27,610
But he lost.

486
00:45:27,647 --> 00:45:29,965
He lost like you.

487
00:45:30,007 --> 00:45:33,620
And this brought great
shame on our people.

488
00:45:33,685 --> 00:45:37,181
And we were labeled tangata hara...

489
00:45:37,247 --> 00:45:39,642
Men of sin, rebels.

490
00:45:39,685 --> 00:45:42,474
I never lost.

491
00:45:42,528 --> 00:45:44,962
Well, why are you here
then, in my land?

492
00:45:45,004 --> 00:45:48,068
Where is your farm, farmer man?

493
00:45:48,127 --> 00:45:50,915
You fought the British and
you lost too, didn't you?

494
00:45:50,965 --> 00:45:52,968
You lost.

495
00:45:53,005 --> 00:45:55,174
And that's not all you lost, is it?

496
00:46:02,124 --> 00:46:04,918
Where'd you learn to track a man?

497
00:46:08,762 --> 00:46:10,725
Hey.

498
00:46:10,761 --> 00:46:13,629
Dabe.

499
00:46:13,685 --> 00:46:16,356
What do you mean, dabe?

500
00:46:16,404 --> 00:46:20,370
Dabe... my father's
houseboy,

501
00:46:20,443 --> 00:46:22,328
Old hottentot.

502
00:46:22,363 --> 00:46:24,327
Hottentot.

503
00:46:24,363 --> 00:46:26,679
Hottentot.
[CHUCKLES]

504
00:46:26,722 --> 00:46:28,764
What's a hottentot?

505
00:46:28,802 --> 00:46:31,042
A south African bushman.

506
00:46:31,084 --> 00:46:33,479
<i>A bushman? I've never seen one.</i>

507
00:46:33,521 --> 00:46:37,316
You never will.
All gone, good as.

508
00:46:39,881 --> 00:46:42,092
Like me.

509
00:46:44,282 --> 00:46:46,639
As dumb as they are,

510
00:46:46,682 --> 00:46:48,645
They will catch you

511
00:46:48,681 --> 00:46:52,374
And probably shoot you.

512
00:46:52,444 --> 00:46:54,407
If I were in your shoes,

513
00:46:54,443 --> 00:46:56,367
Which I am,

514
00:46:56,401 --> 00:46:59,151
I'd just worry about them finding me.

515
00:46:59,202 --> 00:47:01,007
You can't run forever.

516
00:47:01,041 --> 00:47:02,965
One of us will find you.

517
00:47:02,998 --> 00:47:05,626
You best pray it isn't me.

518
00:47:13,919 --> 00:47:16,825
But I'm not the one who's running.

519
00:47:16,878 --> 00:47:19,667
[SPEAKS MAORI]

520
00:47:19,719 --> 00:47:23,293
I think you're the one
who's running away.

521
00:47:23,359 --> 00:47:25,323
And I think...

522
00:47:25,360 --> 00:47:27,737
I think you left your soul behind.

523
00:47:31,675 --> 00:47:33,756
Now untie these

524
00:47:33,798 --> 00:47:36,593
Before I break your bloody neck.

525
00:47:53,035 --> 00:47:55,079
[COUGHING, GASPING]

526
00:47:57,717 --> 00:47:59,844
[PANTING]

527
00:48:06,474 --> 00:48:08,673
Kereama: You know, when
you sail for a long time,

528
00:48:08,714 --> 00:48:10,677
You've got to get on
with all the blokes.

529
00:48:10,713 --> 00:48:12,402
If someone doesn't get on,

530
00:48:12,435 --> 00:48:15,891
We just throw them overboard
at the next port.

531
00:48:15,956 --> 00:48:17,606
With you, I don't think

532
00:48:17,638 --> 00:48:20,849
We would have waited
till the next port.

533
00:48:23,155 --> 00:48:25,825
Your wife...
how did she die?

534
00:48:28,234 --> 00:48:31,141
Did she get sick?

535
00:48:31,192 --> 00:48:33,319
Did she get sick of you?

536
00:48:58,713 --> 00:49:00,363
I'm sorry.

537
00:49:00,393 --> 00:49:02,437
I shouldn't have said that.

538
00:49:16,549 --> 00:49:18,593
Thanks.

539
00:49:25,708 --> 00:49:27,752
Walk.

540
00:49:32,706 --> 00:49:35,849
- What is this?
- Biltong.

541
00:49:35,908 --> 00:49:38,619
I'd rather die of starvation.

542
00:49:43,389 --> 00:49:45,558
Right here.

543
00:49:50,107 --> 00:49:52,610
Something here.

544
00:49:59,148 --> 00:50:01,112
Blood.

545
00:50:01,147 --> 00:50:03,441
Fighting or...

546
00:50:04,986 --> 00:50:06,988
Which way?

547
00:50:13,505 --> 00:50:15,548
Van Diemen:
<i>Come.</i>

548
00:50:15,588 --> 00:50:17,316
Kereama:
<i>Wouldn't it be easier</i>

549
00:50:17,348 --> 00:50:19,390
<i>If we just wait for the River to calm down?</i>

550
00:50:19,426 --> 00:50:22,017
No, I'm not taking chances
with the rain,

551
00:50:22,065 --> 00:50:23,989
Not in this bloody country.

552
00:50:24,025 --> 00:50:27,285
It's not going to rain.

553
00:50:27,344 --> 00:50:29,504
I'm a sailor.
I can tell you the weather

554
00:50:29,547 --> 00:50:31,674
From the color of the water.

555
00:50:36,666 --> 00:50:39,179
I lied, okay?
I lied.

556
00:50:39,222 --> 00:50:41,186
Come.

557
00:50:41,223 --> 00:50:44,640
You're taking me back to be hanged

558
00:50:44,704 --> 00:50:46,981
For something I didn't even do.

559
00:50:47,022 --> 00:50:48,986
Huh?

560
00:50:49,023 --> 00:50:51,497
What would you do, huh?
What?

561
00:50:51,545 --> 00:50:54,530
Oh, Mr. Silence now, huh?
Mr. Silence?

562
00:50:54,583 --> 00:50:56,978
You say another word...
I'll hang you myself

563
00:50:57,022 --> 00:50:59,457
From that bloody tree
over there. You follow?

564
00:50:59,505 --> 00:51:02,137
Oh, you lie as well.

565
00:51:02,183 --> 00:51:03,557
Huh?

566
00:51:03,582 --> 00:51:06,135
Jezus christus allemachtig!

567
00:51:06,181 --> 00:51:08,144
You lie just by saying nothing.

568
00:51:08,181 --> 00:51:09,673
In fact,

569
00:51:09,701 --> 00:51:12,176
Everything you don't say
is one big lie.

570
00:51:12,222 --> 00:51:14,420
What in God's name
are you talking about?

571
00:51:14,463 --> 00:51:17,448
Well, that's the second
question you've ever asked me.

572
00:51:17,505 --> 00:51:19,350
You going to answer it?

573
00:51:19,380 --> 00:51:22,090
Well, you just said you'll hang
me if I said another word.

574
00:51:22,143 --> 00:51:24,479
Argh!
Come, you, come.

575
00:51:29,181 --> 00:51:31,066
Walk.

576
00:51:31,101 --> 00:51:33,979
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

577
00:51:48,258 --> 00:51:50,221
Your wife...

578
00:51:50,259 --> 00:51:52,104
She died in that war, didn't she?

579
00:51:52,138 --> 00:51:54,023
It's none of your concern.

580
00:51:54,060 --> 00:51:56,338
- She did, didn't she?
- It's none of your concern.

581
00:51:56,380 --> 00:51:58,029
I was just asking.

582
00:51:58,060 --> 00:52:00,024
Why do you...?

583
00:52:00,062 --> 00:52:01,939
No.

584
00:52:02,979 --> 00:52:04,472
I just...

585
00:52:04,498 --> 00:52:06,972
She never died in no bloody war.

586
00:52:07,017 --> 00:52:08,980
But I thought you said...

587
00:52:09,017 --> 00:52:11,806
I don't know how she died, all right?

588
00:52:11,858 --> 00:52:13,985
All right.

589
00:52:15,858 --> 00:52:20,178
When the sporting British
couldn't beat us,

590
00:52:20,258 --> 00:52:22,811
Lord Kitchener sent his troops down

591
00:52:22,858 --> 00:52:25,843
To burn our farms.

592
00:52:25,895 --> 00:52:27,859
He drove our women and children off

593
00:52:27,895 --> 00:52:30,331
Like cattle.

594
00:52:30,376 --> 00:52:32,339
He penned them

595
00:52:32,377 --> 00:52:36,214
In these
barbed-wire camps.

596
00:52:36,936 --> 00:52:40,039
I don't know how they died...

597
00:52:40,094 --> 00:52:42,843
Sickness, starvation.

598
00:52:42,896 --> 00:52:45,357
<i>There's no one left to tell.</i>

599
00:52:47,337 --> 00:52:50,990
Listen, we both hate the British.

600
00:52:51,055 --> 00:52:53,135
I don't hate the British.

601
00:52:53,174 --> 00:52:55,802
Yes, you do.
I don't hate the British.

602
00:52:57,616 --> 00:53:00,953
I hated my God for a time.

603
00:53:02,576 --> 00:53:04,932
I stood naked in front of him.

604
00:53:04,976 --> 00:53:08,589
I reviled him.
I was so angry.

605
00:53:08,651 --> 00:53:11,322
I thought

606
00:53:11,375 --> 00:53:13,377
I knew him.

607
00:53:15,293 --> 00:53:17,610
<i>Then I remembered</i>

608
00:53:17,655 --> 00:53:22,243
That God did not create
the savage in me.

609
00:53:23,613 --> 00:53:26,322
"though he slay me,

610
00:53:26,373 --> 00:53:28,730
Yet will I trust
in him."

611
00:53:28,773 --> 00:53:32,543
"but I will maintain
my own ways before him."

612
00:53:32,610 --> 00:53:36,155
Mm.

613
00:53:37,492 --> 00:53:39,887
I still think you hate the British.

614
00:53:39,932 --> 00:53:43,271
You think you can get me
to set you free?

615
00:53:43,332 --> 00:53:45,255
Well, I don't know.
You think

616
00:53:45,289 --> 00:53:48,038
<i>That if you could make you and me the same,</i>

617
00:53:48,089 --> 00:53:50,800
That would make me set you free?

618
00:53:53,931 --> 00:53:56,013
I fought for something.

619
00:53:56,051 --> 00:53:59,547
You're just a bloody criminal.

620
00:53:59,612 --> 00:54:02,047
I'm not a criminal.

621
00:54:02,089 --> 00:54:03,974
You're walking on my land.

622
00:54:04,012 --> 00:54:07,860
<i>My tupunas named the
mountains and the rivers.</i>

623
00:54:07,929 --> 00:54:12,211
It's my lineage.
[SPEAKS MAORI]

624
00:54:12,290 --> 00:54:14,842
And I saved your life, bushpig.

625
00:54:14,890 --> 00:54:16,382
<i>It's about respect.</i>

626
00:54:16,408 --> 00:54:18,804
Let me tell you about respect.

627
00:54:18,849 --> 00:54:20,655
During the war me and my men...

628
00:54:20,691 --> 00:54:23,165
We would cut off the trigger fingers

629
00:54:23,210 --> 00:54:25,959
Of the bravest British
officers we captured...

630
00:54:26,008 --> 00:54:28,090
Only the bravest officers, mind,

631
00:54:28,127 --> 00:54:31,073
The ones most worthy of respect.

632
00:54:31,125 --> 00:54:33,324
You understand that?

633
00:54:33,368 --> 00:54:37,163
That's what I did
to people I respected.

634
00:54:44,525 --> 00:54:46,724
Doesn't leave much hope
for me then, does it?

635
00:54:46,765 --> 00:54:49,810
Hope kills fools like you every day.

636
00:54:54,766 --> 00:54:56,848
Sergeant, let's send Corporal Crowther

637
00:54:56,886 --> 00:54:58,495
Back to base for fresh provisions.

638
00:54:58,527 --> 00:55:00,491
This is taking a damn sight
longer than I'd hoped.

639
00:55:00,525 --> 00:55:02,528
Yes, sir.

640
00:55:02,565 --> 00:55:04,999
You'd better show Crowther where
you think we'll be this evening,

641
00:55:05,047 --> 00:55:07,010
'cause I don't bloody know.

642
00:55:07,045 --> 00:55:08,852
It'll just be a rough guess, major.

643
00:55:08,883 --> 00:55:11,469
Yes, I'm sure it will,
Mr. Bryce.

644
00:55:18,724 --> 00:55:20,687
Do you think he's got him, sir...

645
00:55:20,726 --> 00:55:22,690
That Van Diemen?

646
00:55:22,724 --> 00:55:24,649
Without a doubt.

647
00:55:24,684 --> 00:55:26,686
Are the stories they
tell about him true...

648
00:55:26,725 --> 00:55:29,396
You know, butchering our men?

649
00:55:29,444 --> 00:55:31,407
Well, let me put it
this way, private...

650
00:55:31,441 --> 00:55:33,090
If it weren't for the reward,

651
00:55:33,122 --> 00:55:35,440
We'd probably be spared the
trouble of executing him.

652
00:55:35,484 --> 00:55:37,447
I reckon that'd serve him right, sir.

653
00:55:37,485 --> 00:55:38,741
Drake was a good man.

654
00:55:38,763 --> 00:55:41,119
Drake was a trousered ape, private,

655
00:55:41,163 --> 00:55:43,322
A disgrace to his uniform and his rank.

656
00:55:43,361 --> 00:55:45,561
Begging your pardon, sir,

657
00:55:45,602 --> 00:55:47,938
But he didn't deserve
to die the way he did.

658
00:55:50,603 --> 00:55:52,566
No, you're quite right.

659
00:55:52,603 --> 00:55:55,314
Indeed he didn't.

660
00:55:58,682 --> 00:56:01,156
You haven't seen action
yet, have you, private?

661
00:56:01,199 --> 00:56:04,695
No, sir, not as such.
Not yet.

662
00:56:04,762 --> 00:56:06,725
I hope to, sir.

663
00:56:06,761 --> 00:56:10,140
A word of caution:

664
00:56:10,200 --> 00:56:12,360
Just be sure

665
00:56:12,400 --> 00:56:16,320
That when your children
ask you what you did...

666
00:56:18,961 --> 00:56:22,692
What you did in defense of the realm,

667
00:56:22,761 --> 00:56:25,392
That you're able to give
them a worthy answer.

668
00:56:25,440 --> 00:56:27,776
I beg your pardon, sir?

669
00:56:30,157 --> 00:56:32,199
If he's still alive, he'll
be given a fair trial.

670
00:56:32,237 --> 00:56:34,200
If he's guilty, he'll be hanged.

671
00:56:34,237 --> 00:56:36,239
An example will be made.

672
00:56:43,157 --> 00:56:45,159
Te ara ruamano.

673
00:56:45,198 --> 00:56:49,362
The path of ruamano.

674
00:56:49,438 --> 00:56:53,720
He's like our spiritual guardian.

675
00:56:53,798 --> 00:56:57,569
And he's known to save those
of his people in danger.

676
00:56:57,639 --> 00:56:59,406
What?

677
00:56:59,439 --> 00:57:03,860
This... you pakeha
call it Elson's Gorge.

678
00:57:11,714 --> 00:57:14,091
Let me look.
[SPEAKS MAORI]

679
00:57:15,515 --> 00:57:19,561
Look, you can draw your gun
and shoot me.

680
00:57:21,995 --> 00:57:24,352
Don't doubt it.

681
00:57:24,396 --> 00:57:26,752
I will shoot you.

682
00:57:26,795 --> 00:57:30,250
That bullet will cost you
75 sovereigns.

683
00:57:30,311 --> 00:57:33,376
Nice.

684
00:57:33,435 --> 00:57:37,441
North, south,

685
00:57:37,512 --> 00:57:39,475
East.

686
00:57:39,512 --> 00:57:41,598
Oops.

687
00:57:44,556 --> 00:57:46,361
Damn you.

688
00:57:46,392 --> 00:57:48,277
Come.
Come come come.

689
00:57:48,313 --> 00:57:51,221
No no, I don't care much
for that idea.

690
00:57:51,273 --> 00:57:53,510
- I will let you go.
- Let go.

691
00:57:53,553 --> 00:57:55,046
I'll let you go.

692
00:57:55,073 --> 00:57:56,682
Go ahead, let go.

693
00:57:56,714 --> 00:57:58,677
I swear I'll shoot you.

694
00:57:58,714 --> 00:58:02,250
Well, you can try.
But to get your gun,

695
00:58:02,313 --> 00:58:04,747
You're gonna have to let go
of this rope with one hand.

696
00:58:04,794 --> 00:58:07,032
I'll break your bloody neck
if you jump.

697
00:58:07,069 --> 00:58:09,347
Or you could fall in with me.

698
00:58:09,391 --> 00:58:11,590
And with that pack, the rifle

699
00:58:11,630 --> 00:58:14,968
And your fat <i>puku,</i>
you could sink and drown.

700
00:58:15,030 --> 00:58:17,072
I'll shoot you as you fall.

701
00:58:17,111 --> 00:58:19,703
You might miss.
And I might drown.

702
00:58:19,751 --> 00:58:22,187
Ruamano might save me.

703
00:58:22,231 --> 00:58:24,194
But we won't know, will we,

704
00:58:24,230 --> 00:58:27,025
Until you let go?

705
00:58:28,952 --> 00:58:31,579
[SCREAMING]

706
00:59:38,942 --> 00:59:42,446
[PANTING]

707
01:00:12,300 --> 01:00:14,678
[COUGHS]

708
01:00:59,582 --> 01:01:01,388
[GUNSHOT]

709
01:01:01,419 --> 01:01:04,047
[SPEAKS MAORI]

710
01:01:27,578 --> 01:01:29,872
[GUNSHOT]

711
01:01:33,256 --> 01:01:35,550
You wish to fight me?
Come. Come.

712
01:02:08,172 --> 01:02:10,758
Get up.
Get up.

713
01:02:29,094 --> 01:02:31,262
I'm innocent.

714
01:02:35,293 --> 01:02:37,087
I'm innocent.

715
01:02:42,053 --> 01:02:43,513
[SCREAMS]

716
01:02:54,452 --> 01:02:57,201
[GROANS]

717
01:02:57,252 --> 01:02:59,373
What's the matter with you, eh?

718
01:02:59,410 --> 01:03:02,552
I'm just trying to uphold the law.

719
01:03:02,610 --> 01:03:03,945
You're a liar.

720
01:03:03,971 --> 01:03:06,367
It's got nothing to do with the law.

721
01:03:06,412 --> 01:03:08,845
<i>It's for money. You've sold your soul.</i>

722
01:03:08,886 --> 01:03:11,439
<i>You know they're going to hang me</i>

723
01:03:11,487 --> 01:03:13,451
<i>For something I didn't even do.</i>

724
01:03:13,488 --> 01:03:15,413
There were witnesses.

725
01:03:15,449 --> 01:03:17,019
Yes, soldiers.

726
01:03:17,049 --> 01:03:18,384
<i>And a woman.</i>

727
01:03:18,412 --> 01:03:21,200
She's a pakeha woman and I'm a Maori.

728
01:03:21,250 --> 01:03:23,056
It was soldiers who did it.

729
01:03:23,091 --> 01:03:25,840
And it was soldiers
who hung my father.

730
01:03:25,889 --> 01:03:27,970
They made me watch.

731
01:03:28,009 --> 01:03:29,698
Then they forced my head around

732
01:03:29,728 --> 01:03:31,652
And made me watch them
hang my grandfather.

733
01:03:31,687 --> 01:03:34,122
If you kill me,

734
01:03:34,167 --> 01:03:36,838
You will condemn yourself.

735
01:03:36,890 --> 01:03:38,854
They will find you,

736
01:03:38,888 --> 01:03:41,597
No matter how long, how many years...

737
01:03:41,647 --> 01:03:45,339
What's a few years
worth, eh? Eh?

738
01:03:45,407 --> 01:03:47,371
What's it worth to a condemned man?

739
01:03:47,407 --> 01:03:49,370
Eh? Argh!

740
01:03:49,408 --> 01:03:52,038
Do it. Do it.

741
01:03:52,086 --> 01:03:54,672
Do it!

742
01:03:59,647 --> 01:04:02,121
You can't kill me.

743
01:04:02,167 --> 01:04:05,585
You can't do it.

744
01:04:05,648 --> 01:04:09,026
[SPEAKS MAORI]

745
01:04:12,766 --> 01:04:15,101
[SPEAKING MAORI]

746
01:04:18,565 --> 01:04:21,026
[BOTH SHOUTING IN MAORI]

747
01:04:29,326 --> 01:04:31,536
Are you all right?

748
01:04:35,882 --> 01:04:37,845
I'm quite well,
Mr. Bryce.

749
01:04:37,882 --> 01:04:40,239
Thank you.

750
01:04:40,283 --> 01:04:43,464
[SPEAKING MAORI]

751
01:04:43,524 --> 01:04:46,234
You bloody little Maori.

752
01:04:46,284 --> 01:04:48,248
- Carlysle: That's enough.
- Van Diemen: No.

753
01:04:48,284 --> 01:04:50,247
That's enough, Mr. Bryce,

754
01:04:50,285 --> 01:04:53,038
Unless you plan to carry
him back to town.

755
01:04:55,162 --> 01:04:57,126
Sergeant, tie him up.

756
01:04:57,162 --> 01:04:59,399
Renwick, get the rope

757
01:04:59,440 --> 01:05:01,484
And tie him up.

758
01:05:02,800 --> 01:05:04,843
Well, Mr. Van Diemen,
you've obviously endured

759
01:05:04,882 --> 01:05:06,844
- A tough couple of days.
- Yeah, major.

760
01:05:06,882 --> 01:05:10,344
You needn't fret, sir.
100 sovereigns are yours.

761
01:05:11,882 --> 01:05:14,801
<i>Admirable, most admirable.</i>

762
01:05:27,642 --> 01:05:29,605
[KEREAMA GRUNTING]

763
01:05:29,641 --> 01:05:31,852
Come on, get up.

764
01:05:36,479 --> 01:05:39,071
Get up, you bloody savage.
Renwick, give us a hand.

765
01:05:39,121 --> 01:05:41,831
Get up, your murdering bastard, you.

766
01:05:41,879 --> 01:05:44,471
Major, with your permission, if you
tie his hands in front of him,

767
01:05:44,520 --> 01:05:47,583
It'd help him walk easier and quicker.

768
01:05:47,640 --> 01:05:50,153
All right. Sergeant, do as Mr.
Van Diemen suggested.

769
01:05:50,197 --> 01:05:52,575
Sir.
Renwick.

770
01:06:22,757 --> 01:06:25,937
I didn't expect to see you until
our return, sergeant major,

771
01:06:25,997 --> 01:06:29,454
Well, sir, corporal Crowther said

772
01:06:29,515 --> 01:06:32,421
Your orders were for me to bring
supplies with due haste, sir.

773
01:06:32,475 --> 01:06:35,774
I'm sure the corporal
said no such thing.

774
01:06:35,833 --> 01:06:38,347
Well, now you're here, you'd
better get about it, I supposed.

775
01:06:38,394 --> 01:06:40,278
<i>Just remember, sergeant major,</i>

776
01:06:40,315 --> 01:06:42,442
<i>This is not a vendetta.</i>

777
01:06:53,193 --> 01:06:55,509
[MEN CONVERSING]

778
01:06:55,555 --> 01:06:57,597
Carlysle:
<i>Yes, thank you, Saunders.</i>

779
01:06:57,635 --> 01:06:59,471
<i>All right, sergeant major.</i>

780
01:07:10,714 --> 01:07:14,091
Tough bastards, aren't they?

781
01:07:14,152 --> 01:07:17,058
<i>My family fought against them</i>

782
01:07:17,113 --> 01:07:19,574
In the land wars 30 years ago.

783
01:07:21,113 --> 01:07:23,077
Good fighters,

784
01:07:23,112 --> 01:07:25,783
Clever as the weasels.

785
01:07:25,833 --> 01:07:27,796
You face them doing
one of those godless

786
01:07:27,831 --> 01:07:29,795
War-jigs of theirs,

787
01:07:29,830 --> 01:07:31,793
Their <i>haka,</i>

788
01:07:31,831 --> 01:07:34,227
Screaming like a pack of wild dogs,

789
01:07:34,273 --> 01:07:37,100
Mate, you know you're in trouble then.

790
01:07:37,148 --> 01:07:40,251
Fierce.
And the women are worse.

791
01:07:40,312 --> 01:07:42,237
Excuse me.

792
01:07:42,272 --> 01:07:44,941
I should know.
I married one.

793
01:07:44,990 --> 01:07:47,034
[LAUGHING]

794
01:07:53,109 --> 01:07:55,153
Some meat.

795
01:08:07,305 --> 01:08:09,182
<i>Thank you.</i>

796
01:08:11,507 --> 01:08:13,430
<i>Where's he going?</i>

797
01:08:13,468 --> 01:08:17,139
<i>Feeding our meat to a murderer.</i>

798
01:08:19,230 --> 01:08:21,194
What, is he comforting him?

799
01:08:21,230 --> 01:08:24,191
Feeding the savage.

800
01:08:28,188 --> 01:08:31,291
- Thanks.
- Mm?

801
01:08:31,345 --> 01:08:33,430
For this.

802
01:08:38,264 --> 01:08:40,227
You must have been quite a soldier.

803
01:08:40,264 --> 01:08:42,766
I was never a soldier.

804
01:08:45,387 --> 01:08:47,472
[SIGHS]

805
01:08:50,225 --> 01:08:53,249
More like...

806
01:08:53,306 --> 01:08:55,898
We were a small rabble.
We stopped the British,

807
01:08:55,944 --> 01:08:58,696
But only for a short while.

808
01:09:03,466 --> 01:09:05,429
You were fighting for your land,

809
01:09:05,464 --> 01:09:07,898
Fighting for your freedom.

810
01:09:07,941 --> 01:09:10,336
That'll make a soldier out of a man.

811
01:09:10,383 --> 01:09:12,347
Fighting for my freedom?

812
01:09:12,384 --> 01:09:14,702
Well, you were, weren't you?

813
01:09:14,746 --> 01:09:17,652
[CHUCKLES]

814
01:09:17,704 --> 01:09:19,667
I'll tell you about the freedom

815
01:09:19,705 --> 01:09:22,083
I was fighting for.

816
01:09:24,702 --> 01:09:27,923
Late one morning

817
01:09:27,984 --> 01:09:30,811
The day after new year's,

818
01:09:30,862 --> 01:09:34,476
I was riding home to my farm.

819
01:09:34,543 --> 01:09:37,463
I saw dabe for the last time.

820
01:09:38,942 --> 01:09:41,653
He was hanging
from my neighbor's tree.

821
01:09:44,261 --> 01:09:46,421
What, the British hung your dabe?

822
01:09:46,461 --> 01:09:48,425
No.

823
01:09:48,462 --> 01:09:51,465
Not the British.

824
01:09:52,621 --> 01:09:55,293
My neighbor...
he hung him

825
01:09:55,341 --> 01:09:58,482
For stealing a duck.

826
01:09:58,541 --> 01:10:01,604
82 years old.

827
01:10:01,660 --> 01:10:05,623
No old bushman was going
to steal from a white man.

828
01:10:07,058 --> 01:10:09,533
My friend...

829
01:10:09,579 --> 01:10:12,289
He hung him from a tree,

830
01:10:12,338 --> 01:10:15,087
Left him there for six months

831
01:10:15,139 --> 01:10:18,869
As an example.

832
01:10:18,938 --> 01:10:21,452
Did you avenge him?

833
01:10:21,500 --> 01:10:24,249
No.

834
01:10:24,298 --> 01:10:26,576
I went to war

835
01:10:26,618 --> 01:10:28,582
And fought for that bastard's right

836
01:10:28,619 --> 01:10:30,704
To do it again.

837
01:10:32,497 --> 01:10:35,291
That's the freedom I fought for.

838
01:10:41,296 --> 01:10:45,066
Without freedom we're nothing.

839
01:10:45,137 --> 01:10:47,414
When they hung my grandfather,

840
01:10:47,457 --> 01:10:50,252
He called to me...

841
01:10:52,058 --> 01:10:56,890
"it's you now, Kereama.

842
01:10:56,976 --> 01:11:01,689
You must rid us all
of this <i>hara."</i>

843
01:11:01,775 --> 01:11:04,945
The shame?

844
01:11:09,133 --> 01:11:12,040
But I ran away.

845
01:11:12,094 --> 01:11:14,568
That's different.

846
01:11:14,615 --> 01:11:17,201
You were only a boy.

847
01:11:19,696 --> 01:11:23,388
That's why they never hung me.

848
01:11:23,454 --> 01:11:25,790
I wasn't big enough.

849
01:11:27,173 --> 01:11:31,768
Soldiers just threw
the bodies into a hole.

850
01:11:31,852 --> 01:11:35,188
I couldn't even bury them properly.

851
01:11:38,974 --> 01:11:41,685
So I ran away.

852
01:11:45,975 --> 01:11:47,938
But I always knew in my heart

853
01:11:47,974 --> 01:11:50,722
That I had to come back

854
01:11:50,774 --> 01:11:53,877
And set them free.

855
01:11:53,930 --> 01:11:57,504
So that's why you've come home...

856
01:11:57,573 --> 01:12:00,576
To restore your family honor
and your own?

857
01:12:07,451 --> 01:12:11,890
I almost made it.

858
01:12:11,969 --> 01:12:14,889
It's just beyond that Ridge.

859
01:12:17,289 --> 01:12:20,209
But you denied me that.

860
01:12:23,450 --> 01:12:25,870
You denied me that...

861
01:12:27,890 --> 01:12:31,143
You and your dabe.

862
01:13:26,084 --> 01:13:28,322
Carlysle: <i>Saunders, I think
the prisoner will be fine</i>

863
01:13:28,366 --> 01:13:30,410
<i>Without your attention.</i>

864
01:14:23,122 --> 01:14:25,416
Come on, mate.
Come on, get up.

865
01:14:29,238 --> 01:14:31,532
<i>You'll be all right. Come on.</i>

866
01:14:32,718 --> 01:14:34,681
These ropes were cut, see?

867
01:14:34,719 --> 01:14:36,211
Mm-hmm.

868
01:14:36,240 --> 01:14:39,461
He has a way with rope.

869
01:14:39,520 --> 01:14:41,484
- He has a way with rope?
- Mm-hmm.

870
01:14:41,520 --> 01:14:43,915
What, you knew?

871
01:14:43,960 --> 01:14:45,923
You let him go.

872
01:14:45,960 --> 01:14:48,670
It was tough enough catching him.

873
01:14:48,719 --> 01:14:51,232
In God's name, man, do you
really think I'd let him go?

874
01:14:51,278 --> 01:14:54,618
Well, I'll tell you
one thing for sure:

875
01:14:54,681 --> 01:14:57,272
Somebody let him go,

876
01:14:57,321 --> 01:14:59,678
And in a hurry.

877
01:14:59,719 --> 01:15:02,972
He cut through his wristband as well.

878
01:15:17,918 --> 01:15:19,450
We'll get him.
We'll get him.

879
01:15:19,477 --> 01:15:20,969
How is he, sergeant?

880
01:15:20,999 --> 01:15:23,826
The savage beat him pretty
bad, sir, but he'll be okay.

881
01:15:23,876 --> 01:15:25,961
Mr. Bryce.

882
01:15:27,117 --> 01:15:29,081
How long?

883
01:15:29,116 --> 01:15:31,314
Two, three hours perhaps.

884
01:15:31,353 --> 01:15:34,261
But he's in bad condition.

885
01:15:34,315 --> 01:15:37,142
He'll leave an easy trail.
He won't get far.

886
01:15:37,196 --> 01:15:39,159
Van Diemen?

887
01:15:39,195 --> 01:15:42,651
Mr. Bryce knows
his business.

888
01:15:42,714 --> 01:15:45,111
If you'll excuse me, gentlemen,

889
01:15:45,156 --> 01:15:48,117
But I have a score to settle.

890
01:15:51,714 --> 01:15:53,716
[PANTING]

891
01:16:28,791 --> 01:16:31,618
Right, we'll leave camp here.

892
01:16:31,669 --> 01:16:34,301
Major Carlysle, sir.

893
01:16:34,350 --> 01:16:36,313
This had better be
important, Saunders.

894
01:16:36,350 --> 01:16:38,824
I just wanted to ask, sir,

895
01:16:38,869 --> 01:16:40,990
Now that the prisoner
is armed, what your...

896
01:16:41,031 --> 01:16:42,995
Armed?

897
01:16:43,032 --> 01:16:45,309
How armed?

898
01:16:45,351 --> 01:16:48,454
Did Sergeant Leybourne not bring
it to your attention, sir?

899
01:16:48,512 --> 01:16:51,929
The prisoner made off
with Renwick's rifle.

900
01:16:51,991 --> 01:16:54,202
[PANTING]

901
01:17:04,149 --> 01:17:05,994
Carlysle: <i>Unfortunately, it would appear</i>

902
01:17:06,027 --> 01:17:07,833
<i>That the niceties of Justice
are fast becoming</i>

903
01:17:07,867 --> 01:17:10,616
<i>A luxury we can no longer afford.</i>

904
01:17:10,670 --> 01:17:13,222
<i>You have my permission
to shoot him on sight.</i>

905
01:17:13,268 --> 01:17:15,862
<i>However, this is not to be a game.</i>

906
01:17:15,910 --> 01:17:18,226
<i>There's no place here for sport.</i>

907
01:17:18,270 --> 01:17:20,430
<i>I'll see court-martialed any man</i>

908
01:17:20,469 --> 01:17:23,060
Who doesn't kill him cleanly
with the first shot.

909
01:17:23,107 --> 01:17:25,228
<i>Do you understand?</i>

910
01:17:25,268 --> 01:17:27,270
Mr. Bryce.

911
01:18:09,742 --> 01:18:11,744
[PANTING]

912
01:18:56,340 --> 01:18:58,384
Mr. Bryce.

913
01:18:59,742 --> 01:19:01,980
He could have gone one of two ways.

914
01:19:02,022 --> 01:19:03,985
Take the wrong one...

915
01:19:04,021 --> 01:19:06,181
- Mr. Bryce, please don't tell me...
- I'll find him.

916
01:19:06,220 --> 01:19:08,264
Well, do so, and quickly.

917
01:19:31,456 --> 01:19:33,875
[LAUGHS]

918
01:20:16,496 --> 01:20:18,373
[PANTING]

919
01:20:36,854 --> 01:20:38,731
[SPITS]

920
01:21:00,372 --> 01:21:02,541
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

921
01:21:19,772 --> 01:21:21,982
[PANTING]

922
01:21:34,811 --> 01:21:38,022
[CHANTING IN MAORI]

923
01:22:09,808 --> 01:22:12,602
This is a sacred place...

924
01:22:14,085 --> 01:22:17,130
The home of ruamano.

925
01:22:19,169 --> 01:22:21,133
I would come here with my grandfather

926
01:22:21,170 --> 01:22:23,526
When I was a little boy.

927
01:22:23,568 --> 01:22:26,160
<i>I'd have to wait outside</i>

928
01:22:26,206 --> 01:22:28,680
<i>While he entered into the cave</i>

929
01:22:28,724 --> 01:22:31,935
<i>To talk to our spiritual guardians.</i>

930
01:22:33,965 --> 01:22:36,676
Now it is my time...

931
01:22:36,725 --> 01:22:39,121
Time to redeem the <i>mana</i>

932
01:22:39,167 --> 01:22:41,878
Of my fathers.

933
01:23:45,361 --> 01:23:49,407
[WHISPERING IN MAORI]

934
01:24:29,598 --> 01:24:32,226
[CHANTING]

935
01:24:35,916 --> 01:24:38,377
[CHANTING ECHOING]

936
01:24:51,196 --> 01:24:53,239
[CRYING]

937
01:25:07,154 --> 01:25:09,407
[SPEAKING MAORI]

938
01:25:51,231 --> 01:25:53,862
There's only one way out of here.

939
01:25:53,913 --> 01:25:57,291
You know this camp.

940
01:25:57,351 --> 01:25:59,472
Bryce has lost the track,

941
01:25:59,512 --> 01:26:01,430
But only for a while.
That won't last.

942
01:26:08,108 --> 01:26:11,289
We have to get you out of here.

943
01:26:11,348 --> 01:26:14,019
Believe me, they will shoot you down.

944
01:26:14,070 --> 01:26:17,134
I'm still curious to know

945
01:26:17,191 --> 01:26:19,154
Why you cut the trigger fingers

946
01:26:19,189 --> 01:26:21,152
Off the British soldiers.

947
01:26:21,189 --> 01:26:23,978
God tells us it is a sin
to kill other men

948
01:26:24,027 --> 01:26:26,225
Unless you are protecting your home

949
01:26:26,269 --> 01:26:28,233
And your loved ones.

950
01:26:28,268 --> 01:26:31,730
It stopped good men
from sinning again.

951
01:26:37,468 --> 01:26:39,470
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

952
01:26:43,105 --> 01:26:45,107
[SCREAMS]

953
01:26:49,029 --> 01:26:51,115
Get up.

954
01:27:10,305 --> 01:27:12,224
Come.

955
01:27:18,065 --> 01:27:20,813
Bryce was better than...
than you thought.

956
01:27:20,863 --> 01:27:22,827
There's plenty of cover.
If we split up,

957
01:27:22,862 --> 01:27:24,825
We can get around them.

958
01:27:24,862 --> 01:27:26,669
But they'll just keep on following us.

959
01:27:26,707 --> 01:27:28,512
They haven't got us yet.

960
01:27:28,542 --> 01:27:31,095
Look, I can't run. I can't climb.
There's no way around them.

961
01:27:31,141 --> 01:27:33,602
- You have to.
- I can't run.

962
01:27:36,184 --> 01:27:38,478
We may not have to.

963
01:27:39,703 --> 01:27:41,666
It's your life.

964
01:27:41,704 --> 01:27:43,943
No, it's your life too.

965
01:27:43,983 --> 01:27:45,946
And I'm not a killer.

966
01:27:45,984 --> 01:27:48,904
We can fight.
<i>Ja?</i>

967
01:28:07,259 --> 01:28:08,802
[SNIFFS]

968
01:28:09,659 --> 01:28:12,331
I need you to do one thing...

969
01:28:12,381 --> 01:28:14,549
One great thing.

970
01:28:17,342 --> 01:28:18,716
No.

971
01:28:18,741 --> 01:28:19,880
You must.

972
01:28:19,902 --> 01:28:21,630
I won't do it.

973
01:28:21,661 --> 01:28:24,449
<i>You must help me on my
Journey to Hawaiki.</i>

974
01:28:24,501 --> 01:28:25,836
What?

975
01:28:25,859 --> 01:28:28,961
It's the final resting place
for our people.

976
01:28:29,019 --> 01:28:31,179
Don't let them hang me.

977
01:28:31,218 --> 01:28:33,654
<i>I don't want to die like my fathers,</i>

978
01:28:33,701 --> 01:28:36,450
Hung from some post without <i>mana,</i>

979
01:28:36,500 --> 01:28:39,670
Without dignity.

980
01:28:41,938 --> 01:28:44,524
[SPEAKING MAORI]

981
01:28:46,779 --> 01:28:49,365
[SHOUTING IN MAORI]

982
01:28:56,460 --> 01:28:59,092
I'll take it from you.

983
01:28:59,137 --> 01:29:01,597
[SPEAKS MAORI]

984
01:29:02,896 --> 01:29:06,191
[CHANTING IN MAORI]

985
01:29:44,172 --> 01:29:46,341
[GUNSHOT]

986
01:29:54,333 --> 01:29:56,836
Saunders, Bryce, round to the right.

987
01:29:58,450 --> 01:30:00,494
Sergeant, with me.

988
01:30:12,331 --> 01:30:13,999
Damn.

989
01:30:16,530 --> 01:30:18,240
Van Diemen.

990
01:30:27,011 --> 01:30:30,806
Another trophy
for his majesty's Justice.

991
01:30:40,489 --> 01:30:42,649
He had courage.

992
01:30:42,690 --> 01:30:45,025
He needs respect.

993
01:30:53,490 --> 01:30:56,907
Not your soundest economic
decision, Van Diemen.

994
01:30:56,969 --> 01:30:58,264
I have a little saved.

995
01:30:58,287 --> 01:31:01,468
Bugger that.
I'd rather have his head.

996
01:31:01,529 --> 01:31:02,786
The price will be on your own.

997
01:31:02,809 --> 01:31:04,394
Yeah.

998
01:31:24,289 --> 01:31:26,291
[GRUNTS]

999
01:31:28,886 --> 01:31:31,242
We have to take the body back.

1000
01:31:31,286 --> 01:31:33,486
<i>At least have your men bury him, Carlysle.</i>

1001
01:31:33,526 --> 01:31:35,803
We cannot leave him here.

1002
01:31:35,845 --> 01:31:37,731
I'm sorry,
Mr. Van Diemen.

1003
01:31:37,767 --> 01:31:39,811
Enough time has been spent on this.

1004
01:31:54,524 --> 01:31:56,651
- There you go.
- Thank you, Murray.

1005
01:31:58,245 --> 01:32:00,522
You think Bridget will like it here?

1006
01:32:00,564 --> 01:32:02,528
Without a doubt, sir.

1007
01:32:02,563 --> 01:32:05,115
I've ordered the linen
you requested, sir.

1008
01:32:05,163 --> 01:32:07,991
It'll be here in plenty of time
for your wife's arrival.

1009
01:32:08,044 --> 01:32:10,630
[MAN COUGHING]

1010
01:32:17,682 --> 01:32:19,685
He's alive.

1011
01:32:19,725 --> 01:32:22,631
Sergeant!
Sergeant Leybourne.

1012
01:32:22,681 --> 01:32:24,645
I want a man in every
port, every harbor

1013
01:32:24,681 --> 01:32:27,784
On the lookout for a Maori with
his right index finger missing.

1014
01:32:27,841 --> 01:32:31,469
Now, damn it. I want him arrested
and brought here alive.

1015
01:33:05,919 --> 01:33:07,883
Van Diemen.

1016
01:33:07,918 --> 01:33:10,313
Major.

1017
01:33:10,359 --> 01:33:12,322
I heard you were leaving us.

1018
01:33:12,359 --> 01:33:15,112
This country has no interest for me.

1019
01:33:20,598 --> 01:33:23,269
Australia?

1020
01:33:23,320 --> 01:33:26,031
There's a place they've named
Van Diemen's land there.

1021
01:33:26,080 --> 01:33:29,025
Mm, I like the sound of it.

1022
01:33:29,077 --> 01:33:31,079
Leaving without your reward?

1023
01:33:33,396 --> 01:33:35,399
Woman:
<i>Thank you.</i>

1024
01:33:35,436 --> 01:33:37,399
Man:
<i>There we go.</i>

1025
01:33:37,437 --> 01:33:40,190
25 sovereigns.

1026
01:33:42,518 --> 01:33:45,149
It could have been four times that.

1027
01:33:45,197 --> 01:33:47,199
Mm.

1028
01:33:50,317 --> 01:33:53,028
He's alive, isn't he?

1029
01:33:55,678 --> 01:33:57,642
It must have been
like old times for you.

1030
01:33:57,677 --> 01:34:00,930
He didn't even scream
when you cut his finger off.

1031
01:34:32,992 --> 01:34:35,269
I suppose you have your reasons.

1032
01:34:35,310 --> 01:34:39,314
I suppose I'll never quite
understand what they are.

1033
01:34:41,272 --> 01:34:44,493
It's quite the sum.

1034
01:34:44,553 --> 01:34:47,180
But why so generous?

1035
01:34:49,552 --> 01:34:52,430
You were there, weren't you?

1036
01:34:57,432 --> 01:35:00,602
Did you give the order?

1037
01:35:02,269 --> 01:35:05,897
Did you give the order
to burn down my farm?

1038
01:35:08,350 --> 01:35:10,519
No, I did not.

1039
01:35:14,031 --> 01:35:16,075
Oh.

1040
01:35:19,592 --> 01:35:24,227
Tell me one thing:

1041
01:35:24,311 --> 01:35:27,178
Was anybody in the house

1042
01:35:27,228 --> 01:35:30,397
When you watched it burn to ash?

1043
01:35:32,227 --> 01:35:34,191
No.

1044
01:35:34,227 --> 01:35:37,021
I can assure you of that.

1045
01:35:38,549 --> 01:35:41,299
Man: <i>Sir. Sir, we're ready.</i>

1046
01:35:41,351 --> 01:35:43,645
The captain's gonna be
wanting to weigh anchor.

1047
01:35:45,550 --> 01:35:47,552
Yeah.

1048
01:35:49,227 --> 01:35:51,271
Major.

1049
01:35:52,829 --> 01:35:55,248
Van Diemen.

1050
01:36:01,428 --> 01:36:03,472
[GRUNTING]

1051
01:36:10,065 --> 01:36:12,303
You know, I've sent
messengers to every port,

1052
01:36:12,347 --> 01:36:14,891
Every whaling station.

1053
01:36:28,906 --> 01:36:31,492
Seen one of these before?

1054
01:36:33,984 --> 01:36:37,283
<i>At most you've bought him a few weeks,</i>

1055
01:36:37,342 --> 01:36:39,305
Perhaps a few days.

1056
01:36:39,342 --> 01:36:43,073
I sincerely hope it was worth it.

1057
01:36:43,142 --> 01:36:45,499
Do you know what a few days of life

1058
01:36:45,543 --> 01:36:47,837
Means to a condemned man?

1059
01:36:50,383 --> 01:36:52,469
Right about there.

1060
01:38:25,978 --> 01:38:28,272
[INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC PLAYING]

1061
01:42:11,600 --> 01:42:13,227
...The end...